Applying aLMI-X (Xarray-based Python aLMI code) to the GA Aquatic ARD database¶

  • Author: Eric.Lehmann@csiro.au (based on the work of Stephen Sagar at GA)
  • Release date: June 2021
  • Release version: v1.0
  • Contents:
    • Background
    • Setting up the modules and tools
    • Selecting a study region
    • Applying the Python-aLMI-X code to Sentinel-2 data
      • Connect to the Aquatic ARD datacube
      • Set up a data query and load the data
      • Applying aLMI to the Sentinel-2 data
      • Plotting the results
    • Testing Python-aLMI-X with MODIS data
      • Loading and processing the data
      • Applying aLMI to the MODIS data
      • Plotting the MODIS results

Background¶

This notebook demonstrates the application of the Python aLMI algorithm in conjunction with the GA test database of Aquatic ARD data, produced for a selection of Landsat 8 OLI and Sentinel 2 MSI scenes for inland water bodies in Australia.

This notebook is primarily used to check the functionality of the Xarray-based Python implementation of the aLMI code. The first half uses an example of aLMI applied to a dataset of Sentinel-2B data acquired on 2020-07-16 over Lake Burrinjuck. The .ini file and SIOP datasets for this scenario were provided by Nathan Drayson.

The second half of the notebook applies aLMI to an example MODIS dataset loaded from a .nc file (i.e. not extracted from a datacube instance), which replicates the tests used earlier in the development of the Python version of the aLMI code.

Setting up the modules and tools¶

In [1]:
import xarray as xr
import numpy as np
import sys
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import datacube

# access to DEA tools:
sys.path.insert(1, '../steve_notebook/dea-notebooks-stevesagar/Tools/')
import dea_tools.plotting  # or some other submodule
import dea_tools.datahandling

Selecting a study region¶

Specify the study region and check the extent on the map display.

In [2]:
#lat_range = (-35.003, -35.031)
#lon_range = (148.627, 148.655)
lat_range = (-34.92, -35.045)
lon_range = (148.568, 148.747)
In [3]:
dea_tools.plotting.display_map(x=lon_range, y=lat_range)
Out[3]:

Applying the Python-aLMI-X code to Sentinel-2 data¶

Connect to the Aquatic ARD datacube¶

In [4]:
dc = datacube.Datacube(env="water-atcor", config="/g/data/r78/dea-atmospheric-correction-over-water/datacube.conf")

Using Sentinel-2bas an example, you can view the product and measurements available as follows.

In [5]:
product = "ga_s2bm_aard_2"

measurements = dc.list_measurements()
measurements.loc[product]

The ga_s2bm_aard_2 product is comprised of the following sub-products:

  • lmbskyg lambertian sky glint corrected
  • oa observation attributes

Set up a data query and load the data¶

In [6]:
query = {
    #'product': 'ga_s2am_aard_2',
    'product': 'ga_s2bm_aard_2',    # option to search Sentinel 2b
    #'product': 'ga_ls8c_aard_3',   # option to search Landsat 8 
    #'region_code':'55HBT',         # option to use Sentinel 2 granule ID or LS path/row
    'x': lon_range,
    'y': lat_range,
    'time': ('2020-07-15', '2020-07-17'),
    'output_crs': 'epsg:3577',
    'resolution': (-20, 20)
}
In [7]:
ds = dc.load(**query)
ds = ds.where(ds.oa_fmask.isin([1, 5])) #retain only valid water pixels using fmask, masking clouds

The dataset ds of RS data can be displayed as shown below – the data variables within this dataset can be further inspected by opening the drop-down list of variables (small triangle to the left of Data variables) if needed, and clicking on the attributes and data icons on each line in the list of variables.

But first, let's only retain the variables of interest:

In [8]:
keep_vars = list(ds.coords)   # keep coordinate vars
ds_vars = list(ds.variables)
band_vars = [bb for bb in ds_vars if bb.startswith('lmbskyg')]
keep_vars.extend( band_vars )
keep_vars.extend( ['oa_solar_zenith'] )

ds = ds[keep_vars]
ds

Replace nodata values witn NaN, and scale the data:

In [9]:
for vv in band_vars: 
    ds[vv] = ds[vv].where(ds[vv]!=ds[vv].nodata) * 0.0001 * np.pi
ds

Applying aLMI to the Sentinel-2 data¶

The updated Python aLMI code takes an Xarray dataset as input, such as the ds dataset we've just loaded above. The code currently expects this dataset to contain at most one single time slice – a multi-temporal Xarray dataset will not be accepted.

In addition, the code requires a file of input parameters (.ini file), containing various parameters and options that will be used during the processing of the data with aLMI.

In [11]:
# import the main aLMI function:
from aLMI_main import aLMI_main
In [12]:
# define the path to the config .ini file:
# CONFIG_FILE = "./ini_files/aLMI_config_testVDI_S2.ini"
CONFIG_FILE = "./ini_files/burj_aLMI_config_test.ini"
!cat {CONFIG_FILE}

# This is the config file for the aLMI.
# It is read into python using the ConfigParser module that is in the python base package.
# Note that section names are case-sensitive, while parameter names are case-insensitive.

[inputParameters]

SIOP_SETS_FILE = ./data/burj_test_siops_S2_wls.nc

# NOTE: these variable names MUST match the names in the ANN file used as input to aLMI!
# inputSpectrumVarNames = ["Rrs_ANN_412" , "Rrs_ANN_443" , "Rrs_ANN_488" , "Rrs_ANN_531" , "Rrs_ANN_547" , "Rrs_ANN_667" , "Rrs_ANN_678" , "Rrs_ANN_748" ]
inputSpectrumVarNames = ['lmbskyg_coastal_aerosol', 'lmbskyg_blue', 'lmbskyg_green','lmbskyg_red', 'lmbskyg_red_edge_1', 'lmbskyg_red_edge_2','lmbskyg_red_edge_3' ]

# NOTE: useWavelengths must have same count as inputSpectrumVarNames
useWavelengths =        [442.7, 492.4, 559.8, 664.6, 704.1, 740.5, 782.8]
tolerance = 5.0
# (nm)

# components: must contain some or all of "CHL", "CDOM", "NAP"
components = ["CHL", "CDOM", "NAP"]

chunkProcessConfig = {'costType':'RMSE', 'minValidConc':0.00001, 'outputFillValue':-999., 'costThreshhold':100.}

# Possible types are reflAboveSurf|reflBelowSurf|uIopRatio
inputType = reflAboveSurf

SolarZenithBandName = oa_solar_zenith

numberOfLinesPerChunk = 500

verbosity = 1


[outputParameters]

outWavelengthLabels =   [ "442.7", "492.4", "559.8", "664.6", "704.1", "740.5", "782.8"]
# NOTE: outWavelengthLabels must have same count as inputSpectrumVarNames
#       outWavelengthLabels values must be within tolerance of useWavelengths (corresponding array values)

# Possible types are reflAboveSurf|reflBelowSurf|uIopRatio|""    (if "", then outputType is inputType)
outputType = ""
# (may be blank, but need "=" or ":")


[optionalParameters]
# In this section we can specify which optional variables to calculate (and write to the output file).
# Some or all of these config parameters are optional in the config file.

# n_bands
#== _10nm_ file required if any of 'Kd_par_MIM', 'Kd_490_MIM', 'SD_MIM' is specified
SIOP_SETS_10nm_FILE = ./data/burj_test_siops_10nm_int_wls.nc
# if Kd_490_MIM: Kd_WavelengthsRange must contain the value 490 (multiples of 10nm)
##### Kd_WavelengthsRange = [420, 750]
Kd_WavelengthsRange = [440, 750]
# min, max wavelengths (nm) used for Kd_par_MIM, Kd_490_MIM, and SD_MIM calculations
Kd_par_MIM
Kd_490_MIM
SD_MIM

#==> maybe add Forel-Ule output here later on... (?)


# These are optional (but a_wavelength must be specified if any of the a_*_MIM options are specified, to select the wavelength):
# a_wavelength value must be in outWavelengthLabels
a_wavelength = 442.7
a_phy_MIM
a_CDOM_MIM
a_NAP_MIM
a_P_MIM
a_CDM_MIM
a_tot_MIM

# These are optional (but bb_wavelength must be specified if any of the bb_*_MIM options are specified, to select the wavelength):
# bb_wavelength value must be in outWavelengthLabels
bb_wavelength = 559.8
bb_phy_MIM
bb_NAP_MIM
bb_P_MIM


[ggParameters]
#
g0 = %(g0Lee)s
g1 = %(g1Lee)s

#from Lee 1999 AO
g1Lee = 0.17
g0Lee = 0.084
#from Lee 2002 AO
g1QAA = 0.1247 
g0QAA = 0.0895
#from Gordon 1988
g1Gordon = 0.079
g0Gordon = 0.094

ggLee = "    0.084    0.17"
# multiple values

g0LeeFloat = 0.084
Note
In the above .ini file, the bottom of the range of Kd wavelengths Kd_WavelengthsRange had to be changed from 420 to 440 as the 10nm file used here starts at 442nm.

The aLMI code can be applied to the current ds dataset (Xarray) as follows:

out_ds = aLMI_main(ds, CONFIG_FILE)

Plotting the results¶

We can plot the aLMI results (all outputs) as follows.

In [15]:
nvars = len(out_ds.data_vars)
In [16]:
ncols = 2
mm,rr = divmod(nvars,ncols)
nrows = mm + int(rr!=0)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols, figsize=(12,70))
axs = axs.flat   # axs.reshape(-1)   # "flatten" the list of axes

for ii,vv in enumerate( list(out_ds.data_vars) ):
    ndv = out_ds[vv].attrs['nodata']  # no data value
    plt.sca(axs[ii]); axs[ii].set_aspect('equal')
    out_ds[vv].where(out_ds[vv]!=ndv).plot()
    plt.title(vv); plt.tight_layout()

for kk in range(ii+1,(nrows*ncols)): axs[kk].set_axis_off()   # "kill" superfluous axes...

Further plot of the SIOPindex output:

In [17]:
# Replace 'nodata' with NaN:
tmp = out_ds.SIOPindex.where(out_ds.SIOPindex!=out_ds.SIOPindex.nodata)

# Plot the result:
tmp.plot(vmin=-1.0, vmax=4.0, cmap='jet', figsize=(16,10));

Testing Python-aLMI-X with MODIS data¶

For further insight, we can load up the .nc input file of MODIS data (used as a test dataset during the original translation of the aLMI code to Python3) and apply aLMI to that dataset.

Loading and processing the data¶

First read the test MODIS dataset from .nc into an Xarray dataset, and pre-process to ensure we can apply aLMI to it.

In [18]:
nc_input_file = "/g/data/r78/aLMI/data/A20120403_0410.20150928173107.L2OC_BASE.ANN_P134_V20140704.nc"
nc_ds = xr.open_dataset(nc_input_file)
nc_ds

    In [19]:
    list(nc_ds.dims)
    Out[19]:
    ['number_of_lines',
 'pixel_control_points',
 'pixels_per_line',
 'total_band_number']

    The list of dimensions of this dataset includes several "coordinates" that can't be used as input ot aLMI-X – the code expects an input dataset with only two dimensions (x/y, lat/lon, etc.).

    Let's remove the (unnecessary) variables in the .nc-based dataset that make use of the superfluous dimensions – the resulting dataset will then only contain the dimensions of interest.

    In [20]:
    nc_ds = nc_ds.drop_vars(['latitude','longitude','wavelength']).squeeze(drop=True)
print( "The dataset's dimensions are now: ", list(nc_ds.dims) )
nc_ds

    The dataset's dimensions are now:  ['number_of_lines', 'pixels_per_line']

      Applying aLMI to the MODIS data¶

      Given the new dataset of MODIS data, we need to point the aLMI code to a different .ini file of input parameters (MODIS-based, rather than Sentinel-2 parameters):

      In [21]:
      CONFIG_FILE = "./ini_files/aLMI_config_testVDI_MODIS.ini"
!cat {CONFIG_FILE}

      # This is the config file for the aLMI -- for test MODIS .nc file on VDI
# It is read into python using the ConfigParser module that is in the python base package.
# Note that section names are case-sensitive, while parameter names are case-insensitive.
#
# Config file updated for .nc file input to aLMI.

[inputParameters]

SIOP_SETS_FILE = ./data/siops_MODIS_all_CLT4.nc

# NOTE: these variable names MUST match the names in the ANN file used as input to aLMI!
inputSpectrumVarNames = ["Rrs_ANN_412" , "Rrs_ANN_443" , "Rrs_ANN_488" , "Rrs_ANN_531" , "Rrs_ANN_547" , "Rrs_ANN_667" , "Rrs_ANN_678" , "Rrs_ANN_748" ]

# NOTE: useWavelengths must have same count as inputSpectrumVarNames
useWavelengths =        [         411.5,          441.5,          486.5,          528.5,          551.0,          665.5,          676.5,          746.5]
tolerance = 5.0
# (nm)

# components: must contain some or all of "CHL", "CDOM", "NAP"
components = ["CHL", "CDOM", "NAP"]

chunkProcessConfig = {'costType':'RMSE', 'minValidConc':0.00001, 'outputFillValue':-999., 'costThreshhold':100.}

# Possible types are reflAboveSurf|reflBelowSurf|uIopRatio
inputType = reflBelowSurf

SolarZenithBandName = zen

numberOfLinesPerChunk = 500

verbosity = 1


[outputParameters]

outWavelengthLabels =   [    "412" ,     "441" ,     "488" ,     "531" ,     "551" ,     "667" ,     "678" ,     "748" ]
# NOTE: outWavelengthLabels must have same count as inputSpectrumVarNames
#       outWavelengthLabels values must be within tolerance of useWavelengths (corresponding array values)

# Possible types are reflAboveSurf|reflBelowSurf|uIopRatio|""    (if "", then outputType is inputType)
outputType = reflAboveSurf
# (may be blank, but need "=" or ":")


[optionalParameters]
# In this section we can specify which optional variables to calculate (and write to the output file).
# Some or all of these config parameters are optional in the config file.

# n_bands
#== _10nm_ file required if any of 'Kd_par_MIM', 'Kd_490_MIM', 'SD_MIM' is specified
SIOP_SETS_10nm_FILE = ./data/siops_10nm_all_CLT4.nc
# if Kd_490_MIM: Kd_WavelengthsRange must contain the value 490 (multiples of 10nm)
Kd_WavelengthsRange = [420, 750]
# min, max wavelengths (nm) used for Kd_par_MIM, Kd_490_MIM, and SD_MIM calculations
Kd_par_MIM
Kd_490_MIM
SD_MIM

#==> maybe add Forel-Ule output here later on... (?)


# These are optional (but a_wavelength must be specified if any of the a_*_MIM options are specified, to select the wavelength):
# a_wavelength value must be in outWavelengthLabels
a_wavelength = 441
a_phy_MIM
a_CDOM_MIM
a_NAP_MIM
a_P_MIM
a_CDM_MIM
a_tot_MIM

# These are optional (but bb_wavelength must be specified if any of the bb_*_MIM options are specified, to select the wavelength):
# bb_wavelength value must be in outWavelengthLabels
bb_wavelength = 551
bb_phy_MIM
bb_NAP_MIM
bb_P_MIM


[ggParameters]
#
g0 = %(g0Lee)s
g1 = %(g1Lee)s

#from Lee 1999 AO
g1Lee = 0.17
g0Lee = 0.084
#from Lee 2002 AO
g1QAA = 0.1247 
g0QAA = 0.0895
#from Gordon 1988
g1Gordon = 0.079
g0Gordon = 0.094

ggLee = "    0.084    0.17"
# multiple values

g0LeeFloat = 0.084
      In [22]:
      # Run the aLMI code on the MODIS dataset:
out_ds = aLMI_main(nc_ds, CONFIG_FILE)

        nvars = len(list(out_ds.data_vars))
ncols = 3
mm,rr = divmod(nvars,ncols)
nrows = mm + int(rr!=0)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols, figsize=(14,50))
axs = axs.flat   # "flatten" the list of axes

for ii,vv in enumerate( list(out_ds.data_vars) ):
    ndv = out_ds[vv].attrs['nodata']  # no data value
    plt.sca(axs[ii]); axs[ii].set_aspect('equal')
    out_ds[vv].where(out_ds[vv]!=ndv).plot()
    plt.title(vv); plt.tight_layout()

for kk in range(ii+1,(nrows*ncols)): axs[kk].set_axis_off()   # kill superfluous axes...
